The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Thursday, January 08, 2004 				 Bus bloc takes sting out of strike
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 																								Calcutta, Jan. 7: The Bengal Bus Syndicate, which controls a majority of buses in and around the city, today said it will not participate in the strike called on January 20 by the Joint Council of Bus Syndicate. 																								Bengal Bus Syndicate president Swarna Kamal Saha said they will opt for a strike if the government fails to address the issues of hike in fuel prices and enhanced road tax. 																								We have given a 15-day notice to the government, requesting it to look into our grievances. We shall resort to a strike if the demands are not met within the stipulated time, he added. 																								Saha said representatives of his syndicate will call on transport minister Subhas Chakraborty tomorrow to discuss the contentious issues.																								Joint Council of Bus Syndicate secretary Sadhan Das confirmed they would go ahead with the January 20 strike. Taxis have also threatened to go off the roads that day. Jute strike 																								A tripartite conciliation meeting held by labour minister Mohammad Amin to end the indefinite strike in the jute industry today ended inconclusively. Another round of meeting has been fixed for Thursday.
